<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="25" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[299,1172,1656,2770]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
DESCRIPTION.—Form: As in 
<emphasis box="[833,863,1945,1982]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">X</emphasis>
. microtretus, but easily distinguished by the form of the pronotum, smaller eyes, and presence of eight 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[911,1010,2036,2073]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">rather</emphasis>
than six rows of punctures 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[623,664,2082,2119]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">on</emphasis>
each elytron.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[299,1172,1656,2770]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[340,450,2131,2167]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Color:</emphasis>
Head and body rufous; pronotum and elytra moderately 
<emphasis box="[606,763,2176,2213]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">iridescent</emphasis>
; appendages testaceous.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[299,1172,1656,2770]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Head: Very broad between eyes; frontal furrows shallowly impressed and prolonged to posterior margin of eye; separated from supraorbital setigerous pores by narrow and sharp carinae; eyes small and nearly flat.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[299,1172,1656,2770]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[560,741,2453,2490]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="27.[1231,1321,1003,1028]" captionTargetBox="[1288,2040,511,975]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURE 44. -Pronotum, dorsal aspect, of Xystosomus polytretus, female, Nova Friburgo, Brazil." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3828557" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3828557/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Figure 44</figureCitation>
): Transverse-trapezoidal (W/L, 1.54); lateral setigerous pores present only at hind angles; laterobasal carinae rudimentary; hind angles about 90°, sides anterior to angles 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1103,1172,2590,2627]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">convergent</emphasis>
to anterior angles; side margins narrowly explanate basally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[299,1172,1656,2770]" lastBlockId="28.[1241,2106,2081,2769]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[339,455,2729,2765]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Elytra:</emphasis>
Each elytron with eight rows of serial punctures, rows 2-7 effaced before apex; punctures large and coarse, separated by about their own 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2056,2101,2127,2164]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">diameter</emphasis>
; side margins moderately explanate; 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2048,2103,2173,2210]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">humeral</emphasis>
projection small, obtuse; chaetotaxy as in 
<taxonomicName box="[1241,1377,2264,2301]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
<emphasis box="[1241,1271,2264,2301]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">X</emphasis>
. gruti
</taxonomicName>
; plica long, evident externally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[1241,2106,2081,2769]" box="[1280,1820,2312,2349]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[1280,1613,2312,2349]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Microsculpture: As</emphasis>
in 
<taxonomicName box="[1673,1814,2312,2349]" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Xystosomus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="25" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gruti">
<emphasis box="[1673,1703,2312,2349]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">X</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1729,1814,2312,2348]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">gruti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis box="[1815,1820,2312,2348]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">.</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[1241,2106,2081,2769]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[1280,1454,2358,2394]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Secondary</emphasis>
sexual characters: Male genitalia 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2049,2104,2357,2394]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">unknown</emphasis>
. Female genitalia characteristic of the species group.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[1241,2106,2081,2769]" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis box="[1281,1361,2495,2531]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="25">Size:</emphasis>
One specimen: length, 4.0 mm; width, 1.9 mm.
</paragraph>
